  <div data-page-zine="1">
    <div class="number">1</div>
    <h1>Publishing<br />Between the Lines</h1>
    <p>
      Guerrilla tactics in publishing counter-cultural materials through
      existing corporate frameworks.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div data-page-zine="2">
    <p style="margin-block-end: auto;">
      The use of corporate tools and ecosystems for counter-cultural purposes
      exists in a rich and storied history. By appropriating corporate tools and
      imagery, artists use a form of targeted subterfuge to more easily
      disseminate ephemera through pre-existing visual lexicons, infrastructure,
      and platforms.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div data-page-zine="3">
    <h2>1.1 Design</h2>
    <p style="margin-block-end: auto;">
      The co-optation of mass-media design by counter-cultural movements in the
      20th century represented a strategic blurring of aesthetic boundaries to
      broaden the appeal and accessibility of radical content. By adopting the
      familiar look and feel of mainstream newspapers, magazines, and
      advertisements, counter-culture artists and activists repurposed these
      formats to disseminate shocking messages to the larger public that
      challenged societal norms and advocated for political and social change.
    </p>
  </div>
